Really appreciate this Oxford Union discussion on Bangladesh. Almost all of the speakers mentioned something about Bangladesh's struggle to secure independence from the evil Pakistanis. Dr. Kamal Hussein mentions how the East Pakistan tried to impose an official religion, i.e. Islam, on West Pakistan (Bangladesh) when Bangladeshi's wanted a secular state. Let us not forget that at the end of WWII the British Empire could no longer afford to hold onto its largest colony of the Indian Subcontinent. When the British proposed to give the Indian Subcontinent its independence, the Hindus and the Muslims immediately started to fight over how to divide up the Indian Subcontinent. The Hindus wanted one country for the Indian Subcontinent, while the Muslims wanted their own separate country from the Hindus and other religious groups. So the British government created Pakistan for the Muslims where current Pakistan was East Pakistan and Bangladesh was West Pakistan. Pakistan was split by India in the middle. Most Hindus moved to India. There were horrendous mass killings between Hindus and Muslims during this mass migration. The Pakistani central government was based in East Pakistan. At some point, West Pakistan became disgruntled and fought for independence. When East Pakistan send their military to defeat West Pakistani Independence movement the Indian Hindus decided to send its military into West Pakistan to help defeat East Pakistani military, and secure independence for Bangladesh. Bangladesh was able to secure its independence and create a secular government with no official religion. Except according to Dr. Gowher Rizvi Bangladesh Constitution does have a clause acknowledging Islam as the religion for the vast majority of its people. So this separation of God and State is not absolute like the US or France. From what I have read the reason India helped Bangladesh fight for independence is due to the fact that Muslims created a separate state from the Hindus of India. Bangladesh wanted independence not because it wanted a secular state. Bangladeshis felt that East Pakistan government was ignoring West Pakistanis' rights. Again from most BBC documentaries its seems Bangladeshis were not worried about creating a secular state, but resented East Pakistan's rule over West Pakistan or Bangladesh.

It is good to see academic institutions like Oxford helping third-world countries like Bangladesh in developing its society. I had been traveling in India and Pakistan in 2016. My travel guides in India and Pakistan had informed me that while Pakistan and India are far behind the developed countries in Western Europe, Bangladesh is miserably behind India and Pakistan. As a result, I have to conclude that there is very little or practically no development in Bangladesh when compared to the under-developed countries of India and Pakistan. it is also disturbing that the host of Oxford Union would make up a lie about the average age of death in Bangladesh has exceeded the average age of death in India. Denigrating India to make Bangladesh look good is counterproductive. I have also noticed that most of the speakers praise government policies and NGOs (disturbing how people invent words that have no basis in reality) for implementing the correct programs that improve the lives of the average Bangladesh citizens. When we look at the development of Western Europe and the US, it is private citizens working in their own professions, creating new machines and new services, and establishing profitable businesses that have significantly raised the standard of living of their own people. Yes, the governments of Western Europe and the US enacted laws (or policies) that help promote trade and industrialization, which helped all businesses to compete, but it is the private citizens themselves who made the most significant contribution to the development of their society. What the 4 speakers are advocating is a socialist-communist approach to economic development or trade development. We know that this type of centralized 5 to 10 year planning or top-down command economies do not work. Sir Paul Collier brings up an excellent point. While Saudi Arabia had fossil fuel, i.e. petroleum, to sell and make an incredible amount of money. Most agrarian countries are not blessed with a raw resource that fuel the industrialized trading system of developed countries (Western Europe, the US, Canada, Japan, & South Korea). So these third-world countries must progress through the difficult process of changing their society and use the ingenuity of its people to industrialized just like Western Europe, the US, Canada, Japan, and South Korea. Clearly, Saudi Arabia and most of the oil producing countries of the Arabian Peninsula are living a materially abundant existence, but they have not made any essential changes that would enable them to become a modern, industrialized nation. But in the absence of a profitable resource, Bangladesh must undertake the herculean task of transforming its society into a modern, industrialized, democracy, with a republic form of government, under the rule of law. This is very hard to do. As Dr. Kamal Hussein mentions that garment workers living in slums are having their the houses taken from them by somebody (Dr. Hussein probably means profit seeking housing developers). The underlying problem is Bangladesh, as a "backward" country, does not have well defined property law. Many poor people like garment workers simply move onto land and build a house. They did not pay for that land. The government does not keep records of well defined property boundaries. Primitive societies do not keep track of property ownership, which depend on a capitalist system where ownership is protected by the rule of law. The poor garment workers simply took that land as "squatters". Now the garment workers or squatters expect the land they took for free to belong to them. There is no clear property ownership in these primitive societies like Bangladesh. So it is easy for socialist-communist like Dr. Kamal Hussein to complain about evil property developers taking land from poor garment workers. The problem is Bangladesh is a primitive society with no rule of clearly defined law. Yet Bangladesh is trying to enter the modern industrialized age. Is that possible? Then Dr. Kamal Hussein goes on rambling about confrontation, consensus, and tolerance. Maybe we should all hold hands and sing kumbaya? Bangladesh is a primitive society where private property is not clearly defined. The government does not even keep track of property boundaries. So what is Dr. Kamal Hussein talking about? Then Dr. Kamal Hussein rambles on about fraudulent votes, buying votes, and how money undermines the democratic process. At least I think that is what he saying. Dr. Kamal Hussein is either a Marxist-Socialist-Communist or he is misguided Muslim. He does not see that getting people to a higher standard of living where they have enough to eat, a decent house, and a DECENT education for themselves & their children is the most important. When people have these things they will not sell their vote. The people elect their government representatives, these representatives make the laws, and individual property rights must be protected. Then people will give their best effort to make the best life for themselves. No, Dr. Kamal Hussein views this type of self-serving greed will undermine democracy. This is the problem of primitive religious interpretation and 19th century Marxism. They do not understand liberalism. Dr. Gowher Rizvi said many positive things about Bangladesh and its political system. These are very encouraging and its shows Bangladeshi's commitment to further development. Dr. Gowher Rizvi also mention that since Bangladesh's independence from its parent Pakistan, the weakness of its democracy is due to the fact that Bangladesh has spent half of its time under military takeover and rule. This challenge is almost identical to the Islamic Republic of Pakistan, Bangladesh's parent country. Bangledesh's achievements should be applauded and encouraged, but Bangladesh have inherited the challenges of the Islamic Republic of Pakistan. In fact, if you look around the world. In the Near-East, Middle-East, Arabian Peninsula, Indonesia, Africa, ... or any country with a strong Islamic tradition you see the military suppressing democratically elected governments with armed military rule. Many under-developed countries, whether Islamic or some other religion, you see military dictatorship burying legitimately elected democratic governments. Why is that? Might makes right, a primitive form of governance since the dawn of humanity, still rule much of the world. Can a society where might makes right still guide the thinking of its people achieve a modern, industrialized democratic republic? I do not think so. I hope Bangladesh will make it.

Dear Gowher:  In hindsight, I think I should have written this letter ten years back, days after you became the International Affairs Adviser to the Prime Minister of Bangladesh. I am sorry, I failed miserably to perform my duty as a friend towards a very good old friend on time. I should have advised you what I thought and still think would be a good piece of advice to someone who was going in the wrong direction. I know, itтАЩs too late to write this letter when you have already reached that undesirable place, and not only that, you are also enjoying the place and everything about it. You have virtually become inseparable from the place and your associates who live there.  However, I strongly believe that your associates aren't your friends because friends are selfless well-wishers, which they are not. They are simply fortune-diggers, delusional, power-drunk people, who can do anything тАУactually they are doing everything тАУ to remain in their paradise. I am so sad to tell this bluntly on your face, your presence has actually emboldened them to remain there in the main alley of power. They are possibly telling themselves: тАЬIf Dr. Rizvi can do it, we all should do it with greater vigour and determinationтАЭ!  Why I think I should have written this letter soon after you stepped on the stairs of the fake citadel of glory, as I believe what Umar bin-Khattab, the second Caliph of Islam said about one good quality of a good friend: тАЬWhosoever shows you your faults is your friend. Those that pay you lip service in praise are your executioners!тАЭ Sorry, I was delusional as I thought soon you would regret with utmost remorse about what you were going to do! Sorry for my naivet├й and stupidity!  Before I spell out the purpose of this letter тАУ which in no way is an attempt to take you out from the place which has become your permanent abode and haven, where the bartender offers the best of drinks, apparently free of any charges! However, there is a cost, not-so-hidden one, one pays even to enter the bar, let alone enjoying the colour, smell, and taste of liquid in the Bohemian crystal goblet! I write this for our old timeтАЩs sake. More precisely, I write this as I saw you making some blatantly stupid things, full of lies and half-truths in front of a TV camera at a debate or seminar at the Oxford Union, justifying the arrest and torture of Dr. Shahidul Alam who is also a very good old friend of yours, which you have spelled out a couple of times during your interview. I write this because it was the last straw for me, I couldnтАЩt take it anymore!  You know telling some unpleasant truth bluntly on someoneтАЩs face is sometimes like banging your door shut to a very near and dear one. It hurts both who tells the bitter truth to a near and dear one, and also the receiver of the blunt words from an old friend and admirer. Gowher you know this good old obscure mediocre friend of yours is simply overwhelmed by your kindness and deep love for him, for all these years! While some forget and even worse, deny getting any favour from friends, IтАЩm not one of them. You were instrumental in inviting me to give a lecture at St. AnthonyтАЩs College at Oxford, way back in 1991. Then you were the one who asked me to apply for the one-year-long prestigious fellowship at the Centre for International Affairs at the Queen Elizabeth House, at Oxford. You, as the Director of the Centre, played a decisive role in my selection as a Visiting Fellow at the QEH. Without this fellowship, I wouldnтАЩt have been able to write my second major book, and several other journal articles and book chapters. And you did this as a parting gift to this old friend of yours before leaving Oxford to join the Asia Society, in 1994.  My turn of getting favours from you didnтАЩt stop there. You also inducted me in as a member of the editorial board of your journal, Contemporary South Asia, which I held for 16 years. Your strong references landed me to some very good jobs in the US. While referees, in general, write three paragraphs for candidates they support, each time I asked for a reference from you, you always wrote at least three pages, which were full of superlatives in my praise, which I donтАЩt think I was really entitled to!  Last but not least, you wrote a very strong endorsement to my last book, Global Jihad and America, which I believe attracts many to my book. I can go on and on to write more about your qualities, and what you have done to the realms of academia, at Oxford, Harvard, and Virginia. The way you metamorphosed yourself from a world-class historian to a world-class professor, scholar, and analyst of International Affairs, Public Policy, and other areas of research and development has very few parallels. And you know, I donтАЩt get anything by writing all these in your praise. I just call a spade a spade.  I hope you would take this letter gracefully. My criticism of your association with something, which I consider abhorrently stinky is not a criticism of your persona, but your wrong choice. Then again, we may agree to disagree on this. Your defence of the present government in Bangladesh тАУ which some people, including me, love to call тАЬregimeтАЭ тАУ shocks and surprises me; whatтАЩs most surprising is, however, your telling things which are тАЬnot trueтАЭ тАУ hope you wonтАЩt mind my calling them тАЬblatant liesтАЭ! The way you defended the present government confused me a lot. You denied there was no one-party government in Bangladesh. Well, it all depends on how you call a one-party tamasha a multi-party democracy, while ruling and opposition party MPs are sitting on both sides of the aisle. ItтАЩs like Thresa May and Jerome Corbyn sitting side-by-side in the British Parliament!  At a recent Oxford Union debate, telecast by Al JazeeraтАЩs Head to Head programme, what you told the savvy and smart host Mehdi Hasan was least convincing, to put it mildly. I couldnтАЩt believe my eyes when I saw your handsome face on my computer monitor and heard your soothing voice that there had been some irregularities in less than twenty polling centres out of the total 40,000 on the last election day in Bangladesh. By the way, none of my close friends and relatives in Bangladesh could cast their vote. They found polling centresтАЩ doors unopen till midday. The secret for Bangladesh's success is the personal sacrifice of previous generations who worked in extremely adverse conditions in the hope that conditions would gradually improve.
